<BlogCrossLinks title="Words Ending With -ENT — Scrabble Suffix Scoring Guide" />

<p class="text-sm text-gray-500 dark:text-gray-400 mb-6">Published June 15, 2026 · 5 min read</p>

<p class="text-lg leading-relaxed text-gray-600 dark:text-gray-300 mb-8">The -ENT suffix is one of Scrabble's most versatile endings — it creates both nouns (equipment, movement, judgment) and adjectives (different, efficient, confident). At just 3 base points, the suffix itself is cheap, but the words it forms often pack serious scoring power from high-value root tiles.</p>

<h2 class="text-xl font-light text-amber-600 dark:text-amber-400 mt-10 mb-4 border-l-4 border-amber-400 pl-4">Why -ENT Matters in Scrabble</h2>

<div class="not-prose my-6 p-4 rounded-xl border border-amber-500/30 bg-amber-950/10">
  <div class="flex flex-wrap items-center justify-center gap-6 text-center">
    <div><p class="text-xl font-bold text-amber-400">3 pts</p><p class="text-xs text-gray-400">E(1)+N(1)+T(1)</p></div>
    <div><p class="text-xl font-bold text-amber-400">200+</p><p class="text-xs text-gray-400">Valid -ENT words</p></div>
    <div><p class="text-xl font-bold text-amber-400">4–10</p><p class="text-xs text-gray-400">Letter length range</p></div>
  </div>
</div>

<p>The beauty of -ENT is its low tile cost combined with high word-building flexibility. E, N, and T are all common tiles (12, 6, and 6 in the bag respectively), so you'll frequently have the suffix available. The scoring punch comes from the root: EQUIP+MENT uses Q(10), JUDG+MENT uses J(8), and SHIP+MENT uses H(4).</p>

